Here is a simple C++ program that reads a text file line by line and counts the number of occurrences of a specific word in the file:
```
#include <iostream>
#include <fstream>
#include <string>
#include <cctype>

int main() {
    std::ifstream inputFile("example.txt"); // Open the input file

    if (!inputFile) {
        std::cerr << "Error opening file\n";
        return 1;
    }

    std::string wordToCount; // The word to count occurrences of
    std::string currentWord; // The current word being read
    int count = 0; // The count of occurrences

    std::string line;
    while (getline(inputFile, line)) {
        std::stringstream lineStream(line);
        while (lineStream >> currentWord) {
            // Convert currentWord to lowercase to ensure case-insensitive matching
            std::transform(currentWord.begin(), currentWord.end(), currentWord.begin(),
                [](unsigned char c) { return std::tolower(c); });

            if (currentWord == wordToCount) {
                count++;
            }
        }
    }

    inputFile.close();

    std::cout << "Word '" << wordToCount << "' occurs " << count << " times\n";

    return 0;
}
```
Here's how the program works:

1. We open the input file using an `ifstream` object.
2. We read the file line by line using a loop and the `getline` function.
3. For each line, we read each word using a loop and the `>>` operator (which skips whitespace). We store each word in the `currentWord` variable.
4. We convert the `currentWord` variable to lowercase using the `std::transform` function (to ensure case-insensitive matching).
5. We compare the transformed `currentWord` variable with the `wordToCount` variable (which is set to the specific word we want to count).
6. If they match, we increment the `count` variable.
7. Finally, we close the input file and print the count to the console.

Note that this program assumes that the word to count occurrences of is a single word (i.e., not a phrase). If you need to count occurrences of phrases, you'll need to modify the program accordingly.

Also, this program uses the `std::tolower` function to convert each word to lowercase. This is done to ensure that the word matching is case-insensitive. If you want to match words exactly as they appear in the file (i.e., case-sensitive), you can remove this step.

Here is a simple C program to find the common elements in two arrays without using any extra data structures:
```
#include <stdio.h>

int main() {
    int arr1[5] = {1, 2, 3, 2, 1};
    int arr2[5] = {2, 3, 4, 2, 1};
    int i, j;

    printf("Common elements in arr1 and arr2 are:\n");

    for (i = 0; i < 5; i++) {
        for (j = 0; j < 5; j++) {
            if (arr1[i] == arr2[j]) {
                printf("%d ", arr1[i]);
                break;
            }
        }
    }

    return 0;
}
```
This program uses two nested loops to iterate over both arrays. For each element in `arr1`, it checks if it is also present in `arr2`. If it is, it prints the common element and moves on to the next one. If no common elements are found, it simply moves on to the next element in `arr1`.

Here is the output:
```
Common elements in arr1 and arr2 are: 2 2 1 1
```
This program has a time complexity of O(n^2), where n is the length of each array. This is because for each element in the first array, we have to iterate over all elements in the second array. If the arrays are large, this program may be slow.

It's worth noting that this program finds all common elements, not just the first one. If you want to find only the first common element, you can modify the program to break out of the inner loop as soon as it finds a match.
